6. salutem refers to the usual beginning of a letter, salutem dicit. Cf . Ov Epist. 13. 1 Mittit, et optat amans quo mittitur ire salutem. dictare salutem means merely “write a letter.'’ owing to the fact that dictation was the usual custom, dictare came to mean nothing more than write. Cf. Juv. 6. 218

Non unus tibi rivalis dictabitur heres.

Suet. Tit. 6. 1 Cum patris nomine et epistulas ipse dictaret et edicta con- scriberet. Sidon. Epist. 1. 7 dominum dictasse profitebatur, se dictasse pro·- clmnat, quod ipse dictasset. Numerous other examples are cited in the Thesaurus. This use became very common in the Middle Ages; see W. wattenbach, Das Schriftwesen im M ittelalter, pp. 266 ff.

7. convitia: a late spelling for convicia.
